<text>Using buttons in HTML text box

&lt; Previous | Index | Next &gt;


A button can be created using the following line of code:

&lt;input type=&quot;submit&quot; name=&quot;button name&quot; value=&quot;button text&quot; script=&quot;scripts&quot; alt=&quot;tooltip&quot;&gt;

The type attribute must be set to be &quot;submit&quot;, in order for the button to be created. The word &quot;submit&quot; usually means &quot;submit data to a server&quot;. If a script attribute is set, it means &quot;submit a script to a program&quot;. The text that will appear on the button is given by the value attribute.

The script attribute can be written in multiple lines for easy reading. In other words, you can type in or copy a paragraph of scripts, in which each command is in a single line, such as:

&lt;input type=&quot;submit&quot; name=&quot;button name&quot; value=&quot;button text&quot;
 alt=&quot;This button charges some atoms and remove some.&quot;
 script=&quot;script:mw:1:select atom  1-10;
                     charge 1.0;
                     select atom 11-20;
                     charge -1.0;
                     select atom 21-30;
                     remove;&quot;&gt;

