To view the source, save this page to your disk, enter the authoring mode and right-click (or CTRL+click on Mac OS X without a multiple-button mouse) on the text box.

[This is an embedded simulator.]

To provide a short string of text that will be shown when the user pauses with the mouse cursor over a button (the so-called tool tip), you can use the alt attribute defined in the standard HTML input element.

There are a couple of limitations. The size of a button is determined by the length of the text on a button and the font type given by the system. The user does not have control over the font type and the size. Neither can the user change the appearance of a button (e.g. background color, border and so on).

